      "text": "Absolutely! Here\u0027s the translation of the provided text, aiming for maximum accuracy. If any terms remain unclear after the translation, please let me know.\n\n## Laws of the Maldives\n\n**Law on Construction**\n\n**Chapter One: Preliminary**\n\n**Introduction and Name**\n\n**1.**\n(a) This is a law to develop the construction sector of the Maldives, and to establish the legal framework required for its advancement and operation based on established principles and standards.\n(b) This law shall be called the \"Law on Construction\".\n\n**Objectives**\n\n**2.** The main objectives sought by this law are as follows:\n(a) To facilitate buildings being safe, promoting good health, and ensuring the safety of their users without causing harm;\n(b) To make construction work safe, promote development and productivity, and ensure it is environmentally friendly;\n(c) To ensure that parties active in the construction sector are competent and professional;\n(d) To facilitate the improvement of the quality of construction work and the quality of materials used in construction;\n(e) To establish a board named the \"Maldives Building and Construction Board\" to advise the Minister on matters related to the construction sector;\n(f) To develop and advance the construction sector.\n\n**Policy Determination**\n\n**3.** In accordance with the spirit of this law, and to achieve the objectives of this law, it is the responsibility of the Minister to determine the policies of the construction sector in the Maldives.\n\n**Implementation of the Law**\n\n**4.** The Minister shall bear the primary responsibility for the implementation and administration of this law, and for carrying out the matters specified in this law.\n\n**Chapter Two: Maldives Building and Construction Board**\n\n**Establishment of the Maldives Building and Construction Board**\n\n**5.**\n(a) To advise the Minister in the implementation of policies determined by the Minister under Article 3 of this Law, a board named the \"Maldives Building and Construction Board\" shall be established within the Ministry within 6 (six) months of the commencement of this law.\n(b) The Board established under subsection (a) of this Article shall operate under the Ministry.\n\n**Members of the Board**\n\n**6.**\n(a) The Board shall consist of 7 (seven) members, appointed from the following fields, who possess technical education and/or experience in the field of construction:\n(1) 2 (two) members appointed by the Minister;\n(2) 2 (two) members representing distinct fields from among parties providing technical advice related to construction;\n(3) 1 (one) member representing parties engaged in the practical work of construction;\n(4) 1 (one) member appointed from the legal field;\n(5) 1 (one) member appointed by the Local Government Authority.\n(b) The members appointed to the Board shall possess the following qualifications:\n(1) Be a citizen of the Maldives who possesses the knowledge, competence, and work ethic suitable for fulfilling the responsibilities and duties of a Board member;\n(2) Not have been convicted of an offense with a prescribed penalty in Islam or an offense of bribery within the preceding 5 (five) years, as proven by a court of law.\n(c) The President shall appoint and dismiss members of the Board.\n(d) The remuneration of the members of the Board shall be determined by the President, upon the advice of the Minister of Finance and Treasury.\n\n**Term of Board Members**\n\n**7.** The term of office for members appointed to the Board shall be 2 (two) years for 1 (one) term. In this manner, a member appointed to the Board may be re-appointed for an additional term of 1 (one) year after the completion of their term of office.\n\n**Responsibilities of the Board**\n\n**8.** The responsibilities of the Board are as follows:\n(a) To advise the Minister on matters related to broadening, developing, and advancing the construction sector;\n(b) To advise relevant authorities on matters affecting the construction sector or related to it, and on the measures to be taken for the safety and security of buildings;\n(c) To advise on methods for developing materials, products, and practices used in construction to enhance productivity and improve the quality of the construction sector;\n(d) To advise on the advancement of principles and methods for establishing procurement and agreements in the construction sector, and to advise relevant authorities on these matters;\n(e) To advise state authorities on matters related to the construction sector;\n(f) To advise on ways to develop human resources in the construction sector;\n(g) To advise on ways to enhance the capability and professionalism of companies operating in the construction sector;\n(h) To advise on ways to promote the use of international standards for quality assessment in the construction sector;\n(i) To advise relevant authorities on the required quantities and availability of essential materials in the construction sector;\n(j) To conduct research and advise on methods for improving energy usage in buildings, building maintenance and management, building codes, construction regulations, and building control systems in the construction sector;\n(k) To promote measures for reducing the amount of energy consumed in the development and use of buildings;\n(l) To advise on establishing and maintaining an archive of records and drawings of construction sector activities;\n(m) To advise on the registration of professionals in the construction sector and the maintenance of related directories;\n(n) To assist in the export of construction work and services, and to advise on ways to promote this;\n(o) To share technical advice and information with relevant institutions in other countries to develop and sustain the construction sector;\n(p) To advise on the formulation and implementation of regulations necessary for the development and sustainability of the construction sector;\n(q) To promote measures for increasing the proportion of Maldivians working in the construction sector and to ensure that relevant bodies carry out the necessary actions through them;\n(r) To advise the Ministry in reviewing issues submitted to the Ministry regarding the construction sector under this Law.\n\n**Chairman of the Board**\n\n**9.** The Chairman of the Board shall be a person appointed by the President from among the members of the Board.\n\n**Duties and Responsibilities of the Chairman**\n\n**10.** The responsibilities of the Chairman of the Board shall be to plan and manage the work of the Board in accordance with this Law and the regulations made thereunder, and to preside over the meetings of the Board.\n\n**Resignation**\n\n**11.**\n(a) If a member of the Board wishes to resign from their position, they may do so by submitting a written resignation to the President. Upon receipt of the resignation letter by the President, the member shall be considered to have vacated the position.\n(b) If the Chairman of the Board wishes to resign, the procedure outlined in subsection (a) of this Article shall be followed. However, even if the Chairman of the Board resigns from their position, they shall not be considered to have resigned from their membership of the Board unless they also resign from their membership.\n\n**Non-Participation in Matters of Conflict of Interest**\n\n**12.**\n(a) When the Board reviews a matter submitted by the Minister requesting the Board\u0027s opinion in relation to an issue submitted to the Ministry under this Law, if that matter is one in which any member of the Board has a personal interest, benefit, or stake, that member shall not participate in the review or decision-making of that matter to any extent. If it is not known beforehand that the matter being reviewed by the Board involves the interest, benefit, or stake of a Board member, then upon becoming aware of it, the member shall inform the Chairman of the Board and shall recuse themselves from reviewing the matter and/or making decisions related to it.\n(b) If a situation as described in subsection (a) of this Article arises for the Chairman of the Board, the chairmanship of such a meeting shall be handed over to another member of the Board, and the Chairman shall recuse themselves from reviewing the matter.\n(c) No member of the Board shall, in the performance of their duties under this Law, seek, accept, or be guided by the advice or direction of any party involved in the construction sector, or any party involved in financial, industrial, or commercial activities, or any other party.\n(d) Notwithstanding subsection (c) of this Article, the Board may consult with and seek advice from experts and consultants appointed to advise the Board.\n(e) No member of the Board shall, in the performance of their duties under this Law, accept any form of gift or benefit, directly or indirectly, in their own name, or in the name of a family member, or a person with whom they have a business or financial connection, or in the name of a child of such a person, in a manner that could lead to bias towards a particular party.\n\n**Confidentiality**\n\n**13.** The information received by members in their capacity as members of the Board is confidential and must be maintained as such. Such information shall not be disclosed to any party, except for disclosure to the parties legally required to receive it.\n\n**Board Meetings**\n\n**14.**\n(a) A meeting of the Board shall be held at least once every month.\n(b) A meeting of the Board can be held only if at least 4 (four) members are present.\n(c) A decision of the Board shall be considered made if it is passed by a majority of the total members of the Board.\n(d) The Chairman of the Board shall preside over the meetings of the Board. In the event that the Chairman of the Board is unable to attend, the chairmanship of the Board meetings shall be held by a member elected from among the members present at that meeting.\n(e) If no less than 3 (three) members of the Board wish to hold a meeting of the Board, notice of this shall be given to the Chairman of the Board with reasons. The Chairman of the Board shall convene a meeting of the Board within 5 (five) days of receiving such notice, in accordance with the notice provided.\n(f) The agenda and minutes of every meeting of the Board shall be written and maintained.\n(g) All administrative matters of the Board and the secretariat of the Board shall be maintained by the Ministry.\n\n**Chapter Three: Enforcement of the Law**\n\n**Powers of the Ministry and the Minister**\n\n**15.**\n(a) In order to fulfill the responsibilities of the Ministry in accordance with this Law and the regulations made thereunder, the Ministry shall have the following powers:\n(1) To formulate and implement regulations necessary for the regulation of matters in the construction sector, including those related to safety and security;\n(2) To determine standards to be followed in the construction sector regarding design, practices, products, and materials used in construction;\n(3) To determine, provide, and facilitate training opportunities for the construction sector, and to establish systems for quality assessment and issue certificates of competence;\n(4) To classify and register contractors and skilled workers active in the construction sector to improve the quality of construction work in the Maldives;\n(5) To collect fees for services provided by the Ministry;\n(6) To conduct activities necessary for raising public awareness regarding the construction sector;\n(7) To examine issues related to the construction sector and under this Law and regulations made thereunder, obtain the opinion of the Board where necessary, and take appropriate measures;\n(8) To take necessary actions to achieve the objectives stated in Article 2 of this Law, and to do all other things necessary for the implementation of this Law.\n(b) In situations where a specific power is delegated to the Minister by this Law, and also in situations where a specific power is not delegated, the Minister shall have all powers directly necessary for the implementation of this Law or for the performance of any responsibility assigned to the Minister by this Law, and all powers that facilitate the proper fulfillment of such responsibilities within the scope of this Law.\n\n**Responsibility of the Minister**\n\n**16.**\n(a) It shall be the responsibility of the Minister to formulate the regulations, principles, and systems required for the implementation of this Law, to issue directives as necessary, and to take the required measures.\n(b) In fulfilling the responsibilities outlined in this Law, the Minister shall be accountable to the President and the People\u0027s Majlis.\n\n**Chapter Four: Construction Permits**\n\n**Permits for Construction and Use of Buildings**\n\n**17.** Permits for construction and use of buildings shall be issued in accordance with this Law and the regulations on construction and administrative regulations for construction made under this Law.\n\n**Prohibition of Work Without a Construction Permit**\n\n**18.**\n(a) Except for the circumstances specified in Article 30 of this Law, no party shall carry out any construction work without obtaining a permit in accordance with the administrative regulations for construction.\n(b) If any party acts in contravention of subsection (a) of this Article, they shall be fined between MVR 5,000 (five thousand) and MVR 500,000 (five hundred thousand) Rufiyaa, depending on the severity of the offense, and shall be ordered to immediately cease the work they are carrying out. The Ministry or a party designated by the Ministry shall have the discretion to take appropriate measures. If work is continued despite the Ministry\u0027s order to cease, a penalty of 3% (three percent) of the imposed fine shall be added for each day the work continues.\n(c) If the Ministry becomes aware that any party has carried out work in contravention of subsection (a) of this Article, the Ministry shall inform the owner of the building to act in accordance with Articles 34 and 35 of this Law. Such a party shall comply with the Ministry\u0027s instructions.\n\n**Fees Payable for Construction Permits**\n\n**19.** The Ministry shall have the authority to collect fees from parties applying for construction permits, in accordance with the administrative regulations for construction made under this Law.\n\n**Application for Construction Permits**\n\n**20.**\n(a) Applications for construction permits shall be submitted by the owner of the building. Applications for construction permits shall be submitted to the parties specified in the administrative regulations for construction, in accordance with the administrative regulations for construction.\n(b) In addition to the documents specified in this Law, the documents specified in the administrative regulations for construction must be submitted when applying for a construction permit under this Article.\n(c) If an application for a construction permit is submitted by any party, the issuing authority shall decide on the issuance of the construction permit within the period specified in the administrative regulations for construction, and shall inform the applicant of the decision.\n\n**Obtaining Permits for Civil Works**\n\n**21.** Any civil work that falls within the meaning of construction as stated in Article 99 of this Law shall be carried out only after obtaining a permit from the designated authority in accordance with the regulations made under this Law.\n\n**Obtaining Permits Required by Other Laws**\n\n**22.** When applying for a permit for construction work under this Law, in addition to fulfilling the requirements specified in this Law and the regulations made thereunder, the following shall also be fulfilled:\n(a) If the work requires a permit under a planning law, the planning permit issued for it shall be submitted;\n(b) If the work requires a permit under any other law, such a permit shall be obtained in accordance with that law.\n\n**Approval of Building Drawings**\n\n**23.**\n(a) Applications for the approval of building drawings shall be submitted to the parties specified in the administrative regulations for construction, in accordance with the administrative regulations for construction.\n(b) When applying for the approval of building drawings, the drawings and details designed by a party holding a permit under the regulations for professionals in the construction sector shall be submitted.\n(c) Upon submission of an application for the approval of building drawings in accordance with subsection (a) of this Article, the building drawings shall be approved and a written confirmation of approval shall be issued in accordance with the administrative regulations for construction.\n\n**Issuance of Construction Permits**\n\n**24.**\n(a) Upon submission of an application for a construction permit in accordance with Article 20 of this Law, a construction permit shall be issued to the party in accordance with the administrative regulations for construction.\n(b) Notwithstanding subsection (a) of this Article, a construction permit shall not be issued to any party unless the following conditions are met:\n(1) The fees payable under the administrative regulations for construction have been paid;\n(2) Any fines payable under this Law have been paid; and\n(3) The permits specified in subsections (a) and (b) of Article 22 of this Law have been submitted.\n\n**Responsibility for Technical Work of Construction**\n\n**25.** If there is any issue with the drawings and details submitted when applying for a construction permit for the construction of a building, the responsibility for ensuring that such drawings and details comply with this Law and the regulations made thereunder shall lie with the parties who designed and checked the drawings and details in accordance with the regulations for professionals in the construction sector.\n\n**Cancellation of Construction Permits**\n\n**26.**\n(a) If the actual construction work for a building for which a construction permit has been issued under Article 24 of this Law is not commenced within the period specified for commencement of construction work in the administrative regulations for construction, that permit shall be canceled.\n(b) For permits issued before the commencement of this Law without a specified period for commencing work, if action is not taken within the period specified in the regulations made under this Law, such permits shall be canceled upon the expiry of that period.\n\n**Amendment to Construction Permits**\n\n**27.**\n(a) If an amendment is desired to the approved drawings after a construction permit has been issued under Article 24 of this Law, the amended drawings and details shall be submitted to the permit-issuing authority in accordance with the regulations made under this Law, and a new permit shall be obtained. Upon submission for such an amendment, the construction permit-issuing authority shall issue the permit in accordance with the regulations made under this Law.\n(b) Upon approval of drawings submitted for an amendment to a building, the original permit issued under Article 24 of this Law shall become void. The new permit issued under this Article shall then be effective.\n\n**Circumstances Requiring Permits for Structural Work**\n\n**28.** When issuing a construction permit under Article 24 of this Law, if the administrative regulations for construction stipulate that a permit is required for structural work on a building, the owner of the building shall apply for a permit for such work. Upon application for such a permit, the process for issuing the permit shall proceed in accordance with the regulations.\n\n**Circumstances Requiring Re-Permit After Interruption of Structural Work**\n\n**29.**\n(a) If structural work for which a construction permit has been issued is interrupted for a continuous period exceeding 6 (six) months after its commencement, further work shall only proceed after obtaining a new construction permit from the permit-issuing authority.\n(b) A permit to resume interrupted work as described in subsection (a) of this Article shall be granted after reviewing the report submitted by a party holding a permit under the regulations for professionals in the construction sector, who has assessed the condition of the site, and the proposed method for continuing the work.\n\n**Circumstances Where Construction Can Proceed Without a Construction Permit**\n\n**30.** The following works may be carried out without obtaining a construction permit as specified in Article 18 of this Law. However, such buildings shall be used only after obtaining a permit in accordance with Article 32 of this Law.\n(a) Construction work that is exempted from requiring a permit in the administrative regulations for construction; or\n(b) Work that needs to be carried out urgently due to unforeseen circumstances, where there is insufficient time to obtain a permit in advance. Such circumstances include:\n(1) To protect a person\u0027s life or health; or\n(2) To prevent significant damage to a person\u0027s property; or\n(3) Situations requiring urgent construction to mitigate damage caused by a natural disaster.\n\n**Prohibition of Issuance of Permits for Construction on Risky Land**\n\n**31.**\n(a) The permit-issuing authority for construction shall not issue a construction permit or a permit for amendment to a building in the following circumstances:\n(1) If the land or site for which construction permit is sought, or where the building is located, is or is likely to be prone to natural hazards in one or more ways;\n(2) If the work is likely to cause danger to a person, the building itself, adjacent buildings, land, or site, or if the existing danger is likely to be exacerbated.\n(b) The Ministry and permit-issuing authorities shall publicize information about such locations to identify them as described in subsection (a) of this Article.\n\n**Issuance of Building Use Permits**\n\n**32.**\n(a) A building use permit shall be issued by a party designated by the Ministry in accordance with this Law and the regulations made thereunder, confirming that the building has been constructed in accordance with the approved drawings.\n(b) An application for a building use permit as described in subsection (a) of this Article can be submitted in the following ways:\n(1) For a part or unit of a building that has been completed, by the owner of that part of the building;\n(2) For a building that has been completed in its entirety, by the owner of the building.\n(c) A temporary occupancy permit may be issued by the permit-issuing authority for construction in accordance with the administrative regulations for construction for temporary use of a building. The use of a building under such a temporary permit shall be in accordance with the terms and duration specified in the permit.\n(d) The procedures for issuing building use permits in circumstances described in Article 30 of this Law shall be stipulated in the regulations made under this Law.\n\n**Commencement of Building Use**\n\n**33.**\n(a) Unless otherwise specified in this Law, a building or part thereof shall not be used until a written permit for the use of the building has been issued by the relevant authority.\n(b) Notwithstanding subsection (a) of this Article, the following actions are not prohibited:\n(1) Occupancy by a person for the purpose of building maintenance;\n(2) Use of a building or part of a building during the period specified for a temporary occupancy permit issued under subsection (c) of Article 32.\n(c) If it is desired to use a building for a purpose other than that for which the construction permit was issued, a permit shall be obtained from the authority that issued the construction permit. Use of the building without such a permit is prohibited.\n(d) If any party violates subsection (c) of this Article, that party shall be subject to measures as per Article 90 of this Law.\n\n**Construction Without a Construction Permit**\n\n**34.**\n(a) If the permit-issuing authority becomes aware that any construction work is being carried out or has been carried out without a construction permit in accordance with Article 18 of this Law, that work shall be stopped and the use of that building shall be prohibited.\n(b) If work is stopped or the use of a building is prohibited in accordance with subsection (a) of this Article, a permit to resume such work or use the building shall be obtained in accordance with the administrative regulations for construction.\n(c) A permit shall be issued in accordance with subsection (b) of this Article only after examining whether the submitted drawings and details for the permit comply with the regulations made under this Law and the building code.\n(d) If construction work carried out without a permit as described in subsection (a) of this Article does not comply with the regulations made under this Law and the building code, the work or the building shall be ordered to be modified to comply with those regulations and the building code. The owner of the building shall bear the costs incurred for such necessary modifications.\n(e) It is prohibited to continue work or use the building without obtaining a permit as required by subsection (a) of this Article. Failure to comply with this requirement will result in penalties as per subsection (f) of this Article.\n(f) A party violating subsection (e) of this Article shall be subject to a fine of between MVR 5,000 (five thousand) and MVR 500,000 (five hundred thousand) Rufiyaa, depending on the severity of the offense. If such violation is repeated without rectifying the situation, an additional penalty of 3% (three percent) of the imposed fine shall be added for each day the violation continues.\n\n**Issuance of Work Acceptance Certificate**\n\n**35.**\n(a) If an application is made to obtain a permit for buildings constructed before the commencement of this Law, or for buildings constructed without a permit, the permit-issuing authority for construction may issue a work acceptance certificate in the following circumstances:\n(1) If the work was carried out before the commencement of this Law; or\n(2) If the work was carried out without a construction permit as specified in Article 18 of this Law; or\n(3) If the work was carried out under Article 30 of this Law.\n(b) When applying for a work acceptance certificate under this Article, a report prepared by a party holding a permit under the regulations for professionals in the construction sector, who has assessed the condition of the site, shall be submitted.\n(c) In the case described in sub-point (1) of subsection (a) of this Article, the permit-issuing authority for construction shall issue a work acceptance certificate after reviewing the report submitted under subsection (b) of this Article.\n(d) In the circumstances described in sub-points (2) and (3) of subsection (a) of this Article, the permit-issuing authority for construction shall issue a work acceptance certificate in accordance with the administrative regulations for construction.\n(e) Notwithstanding this Article, the party shall not be exempted from obtaining the required construction permit under Article 24 of this Law.\n\n**Amendment to Buildings or Sites**\n\n**36.**\n(a) It is prohibited for the owner or user of a building or site to alter, modify, close, or obstruct any part of it, or carry out any other action that contravenes the permit issued for that building or site.\n(b) If any party becomes aware of an alteration made as described in subsection (a) of this Article, they shall inform the permit-issuing authority for construction.\n(c) If the permit-issuing authority for construction becomes aware of an alteration made as described in subsection (a) of this Article, it shall notify the owner of the building in writing to carry out the necessary work to restore the intended use of the site or to make the required alteration, in accordance with the administrative regulations for construction.\n(d) A party violating subsection (a) of this Article shall be subject to a fine between MVR 5,000 (five thousand) and MVR 500,000 (five hundred thousand) Rufiyaa, depending on the severity of the offense. If such violation is repeated, an additional penalty of 3% (three percent) of the imposed fine shall be added for each day the violation continues.\n\n**Procedure for Work Carried Out in Violation of the Law**\n\n**37.**\n(a) If the permit-issuing authority for construction finds that any construction work has been carried out in violation of this Law or the regulations made thereunder, it shall submit the matter to the Ministry, and in accordance with the Ministry\u0027s advice and the administrative regulations for construction, measures shall be taken against the violating party.\n(b) If the violating party fails to comply with an order issued by the permit-issuing authority under subsection (a) of this Article, action shall be taken against that party in accordance with the administrative regulations for construction.\n(c) If the party to whom an order is issued under subsection (a) of this Article fails to comply, the permit-issuing authority for construction shall have the power to demolish or remove the structure, or to make alterations to it as directed by the Ministry, to rectify the unlawful work.\n(d) The owner of the building shall bear the costs incurred for modifications made in accordance with subsection (c) of this Article.\n(e) A party violating subsection (a) of this Article shall be subject to a fine between MVR 5,000 (five thousand) and MVR 50,000 (fifty thousand) Rufiyaa, depending on the severity of the offense. If such violation is repeated without cessation, an additional penalty of 3% (three percent) of the imposed fine shall be added for each day the violation continues.\n\n**Procedure in Case of Refusal to Grant Permits**\n\n**38.**\n(a) If the permit-issuing authority refuses to grant any permit required under this Law, or withholds a permit, a complaint regarding the matter may be submitted to the Minister.\n(b) Upon submission of a complaint under subsection (a) of this Article, the Minister shall review the matter within 1 (one) month and inform the complainant and the relevant permit-issuing authority for construction of the decision.\n\n**Chapter Five: Building Code**\n\n**Objectives of the Building Code**\n\n**39.** A building code shall be formulated under this Law to achieve the following objectives:\n(a) To facilitate buildings being safe and to ensure the safety of their users without causing harm;\n(b) To make buildings environments that promote good health and are conducive to well-being for their users;\n(c) To ensure the safety of building users in the event of an incident and to facilitate safe egress from the building in such circumstances;\n(d) To facilitate the design, construction, and use of buildings in a manner that promotes sustainable development.\n\n**Construction in Accordance with the Building Code**\n\n**40.** Drawings and details submitted for construction permits under this Law, and construction work carried out under this Law, shall be in accordance with the building code.\n\n**Parts of the Building Code**\n\n**41.** The building code shall include the following parts:\n(a) Functional requirements that buildings must meet; and\n(b) Performance criteria for buildings; and\n(c) Compliance documentation to ensure the achievement of the requirements stated in subsections (a) and (b) of this Article; or\n(d) A method of verification to demonstrate that the objectives of the building code are met if an alternative method to that stated in subsection (c) of this Article is proposed.\n\n**Gazetting of the Building Code**\n\n**42.**\n(a) After the Ministry formulates the building code in accordance with Article 41 of this Law, the code shall be published in the Government Gazette of the Maldives. Any amendments made to any part of the building code shall also be published in the Government Gazette of the Maldives.\n(b) As the documents specified in subsections (a) and (b) of Article 41 of this Law are technical documents, this Article shall not preclude their publication in English.\n\n**Chapter Six: Quality Assessment of Construction Work**\n\n**Quality Assessment of Construction Work**\n\n**43.**\n(a) In all cases not exempted by this Law or regulations made thereunder, the owner of the building shall appoint a person in accordance with the administrative regulations for construction to verify whether every construction work is being carried out as permitted.\n(b) Violation of subsection (a) of this Article is prohibited. The Ministry or the permit-issuing authority for construction shall take action against any party committing such an act in accordance with the administrative regulations for construction.\n(c) The person appointed under subsection (a) of this Article shall not have any interest in the party carrying out the work or in the owner of the building.\n\n**Tests Related to Construction Work**\n\n**44.**\n(a) The parties carrying out construction work shall conduct tests on the materials used for construction as specified in the regulations for testing construction materials.\n(b) In a situation where an exemption from conducting a test as specified in subsection (a) of this Article is required, an application for such an exemption may be submitted to the Ministry. If the circumstances for granting such an exemption are described in the regulations for testing construction materials, the Ministry may grant the exemption.\n\n**Responsibility of the Person Carrying Out Construction**\n\n**45.**\n(a) If the person carrying out construction becomes aware that any act is occurring or has occurred in violation of this Law or the construction regulations, that person shall inform the permit-issuing authority for construction of the matter.\n(b) The permit-issuing authority for construction shall inform the Ministry of the notifications received under subsection (a) of this Article for the Ministry\u0027s information.\n(c) Failure to provide notification as required by subsection (a) of this Article is prohibited.\n(d) A party violating subsection (c) of this Article shall be subject to a fine between MVR 5,000 (five thousand) and MVR 50,000 (fifty thousand) Rufiyaa, depending on the severity of the offense.\n\n**Appointment of Parties for Quality Assessment of Construction Work**\n\n**46.**\n(a) The circumstances for appointing parties to oversee the quality of construction work under subsection (a) of Article 43 of this Law, the work for which they are to assess quality, and their duties shall be specified in the regulations for professionals in the construction sector.\n(b) It is prohibited for parties appointed to oversee the quality of construction work under subsection (a) of Article 43 of this Law to act in violation of this Law or the regulations for professionals in the construction sector.\n(c) If any party appointed to oversee the quality of construction work commits any act mentioned in subsection (a) of this Article, action shall be taken against that party in accordance with the regulations for professionals in the construction sector.\n\n**Responsibility of the Contractor for Working in Accordance with Permits**\n\n**47.**\n(a) Parties engaged in construction work in the Maldives shall carry out such work in accordance with this Law and the regulations made thereunder.\n(b) Violation of subsection (a) of this Article by any party is prohibited.\n(c) Any party violating subsection (a) of this Article shall be subject to measures as per Article 90 of this Law.\n(d) In circumstances where the administrative regulations for construction permit the use of an entity registered with the Ministry without directly engaging construction parties, this Article shall not apply.\n(e) Construction work shall be carried out in accordance with the drawings approved by the permit-issuing authority for construction.\n(f) This Article shall not apply in circumstances where this Law or the administrative regulations for construction explicitly state that a construction permit is not required.\n(g) If the person carrying out construction work becomes aware of, or if it is generally known that, any act in violation of this Law or the regulations made thereunder is occurring at the construction site, the person carrying out the construction shall inform the permit-issuing authority for construction of the matter.\n(h) The permit-issuing authority for construction shall inform the Ministry of the notifications received under subsection (g) of this Article.\n(i) Failure to provide notification as required by subsection (g) of this Article is prohibited.\n**Unsafe Buildings**\n\n**48.**\n(a) If any party identifies a building or part of a building as unsafe from a health perspective, that party shall report the matter to the permit-issuing authority for construction or the Ministry.\n(b) If the permit-issuing authority for construction receives information about a building deemed unsafe, it shall report the matter to the Ministry. After reviewing the information received, the relevant authority shall be notified in accordance with the Public Health Protection Act to assess whether the building is unsafe. The relevant authority shall determine if a particular building is unsafe.\n(c) If a building is determined to be unsafe by the relevant authority under subsection (b) of this Article, the owner of the building shall act as follows and shall not use the building until its condition is rectified:\n(1) Inspect and prepare a report on the building or its systems in accordance with the administrative regulations for construction; and\n(2) Rectify the situation at the expense of the owner of the building, in accordance with the administrative regulations for construction; and\n(3) Act in accordance with the instructions of the relevant authority under the Public Health Protection Act.\n\n**Dangerous Buildings**\n\n**49.**\n(a) If a building is found to be dangerous or is likely to become dangerous due to age, excessive load, poor construction quality, an accident, or any other reason, the party identifying such a situation shall inform the permit-issuing authority for construction or the Ministry.\n(b) Upon receiving information about a site as described in subsection (a) of this Article, the permit-issuing authority shall inform the Ministry. After reviewing the information in accordance with this Law and the regulations made thereunder, the Ministry may determine that the building is dangerous.\n(c) If the Ministry determines a building to be dangerous under subsection (b) of this Article, the building shall not be used thereafter without a renewed building use permit issued by the permit-issuing authority.\n(d) If the Ministry determines a building to be dangerous under subsection (b) of this Article, the owner of the building shall act as follows:\n(1) Inspect and prepare a report on the building or part thereof in accordance with the administrative regulations for construction; and\n(2) Rectify the situation at the owner\u0027s expense.\n(e) After reviewing the report under sub-point (1) of subsection (d), if the Ministry deems it necessary to rectify the situation or demolish the building, or take any other action regarding the building, the Ministry shall notify the owner of the building of the course of action to be taken within the period specified in the administrative regulations for construction, stating the reasons.\n(f) If the owner of the building fails to comply with the notification issued under subsection (e) within the specified period, the owner shall be responsible for the costs incurred for rectification, demolition, or other actions as per the administrative regulations for construction, which shall be paid to the Ministry.\n(g) If danger arises or damage occurs to a site or person due to the use of a building in a manner contrary to its permitted use, the owner of the building shall be liable for such damage.\n(h) Any party violating subsection (g) of this Article shall be subject to measures as per Article 90 of this Law.\n\n**Construction Work Causing Danger**\n\n**50.**\n(a) It is prohibited to carry out construction work, or modification or repair of a building, in a manner that causes danger or damage to a person, site, property, other buildings, or the surrounding environment.\n(b) A party violating subsection (a) of this Article shall be subject to a fine between MVR 5,000 (five thousand) and MVR 500,000 (five hundred thousand) Rufiyaa, depending on the severity of the offense. If the manner of work is not rectified and the violation is repeated, an additional penalty of 3% (three percent) of the imposed fine shall be added for each day the violation continues.\n(c) If the permit-issuing authority for construction receives information that construction work is being carried out in contravention of subsection (a) of this Article, it shall take the following actions:\n(1) Order the immediate cessation of construction work if the work poses or is likely to pose a danger; and\n(2) Request the party carrying out the work and the owner of the building to submit a report detailing the causes of such danger and the measures to mitigate it; and\n(3) Based on the report submitted under sub-point (2), permit the continuation of work if deemed appropriate, or permit continuation after rectification if deemed appropriate; and\n(4) If it is deemed inappropriate to continue work based on the report submitted under sub-point (2), notify the owner of the building of the course of action to be taken regarding the building within the period specified in the administrative regulations for construction, stating the reasons.\n(d) If the party subject to notification under subsection (c) of this Article fails to comply with the notification within the specified period, that party shall be liable for rectification costs as per the administrative regulations for construction, payable to the Ministry. However, if the Ministry or a designated party carries out the rectification, the costs shall be borne by the owner of the building.\n\n**Inspection and Checking of Ongoing or Completed Construction Work**\n\n**51.**\n(a) To assess the quality of ongoing or completed construction work, the Ministry or the permit-issuing authority for construction may, upon notifying the owner of the building in writing, enter the site to inspect the work in accordance with the administrative regulations for construction, and the owner of the building shall grant permission for such entry.\n(b) When the Ministry or the permit-issuing authority for construction seeks entry to a construction site under subsection (a) of this Article, the relevant documents, books, or records pertaining to the work shall be presented to that party in accordance with the administrative regulations for construction.\n(c) The Ministry or the permit-issuing authority for construction may create an access point to the construction site in accordance with the administrative regulations for construction. A sample of any material used for construction may be taken free of charge by the Ministry or a designated party for analysis, in the quantity required for testing, in accordance with the administrative regulations for construction.\n(d) If, after inspecting a building under subsection (a) of this Article, the Ministry or the permit-issuing authority for construction determines that an assessment of the building is required, the owner of the building shall prepare and submit a report of the assessment to the Ministry or the designated authority in accordance with the administrative regulations for construction.\n(e) If, after reviewing the report under subsection (d) of this Article, any quality issue is identified in the building, the Ministry or the permit-issuing authority for construction shall notify the owner of the building to rectify the building.\n(f) It is prohibited for any person to obstruct the work of personnel from the Ministry or the permit-issuing authority for construction when they enter a construction site for inspection under subsection (a) of this Article.\n(g) If the owner of the building fails to comply with the notification issued by the Ministry or the permit-issuing authority for construction under subsections (a), (d), or (e) of this Article, that party shall be subject to a fine between MVR 5,000 (five thousand) and MVR 500,000 (five hundred thousand) Rufiyaa, depending on the severity of the offense. If the violation is repeated without cessation, an additional penalty of 3% (three percent) of the imposed fine shall be added for each day the violation continues.\n(h) Details of inspections and reports conducted under subsections (a) and (d) of this Article shall be submitted by the permit-issuing authority for construction to the Ministry within the period specified in the administrative regulations for construction.\n\n**Chapter Seven: Maintaining the Quality of Construction Materials**\n\n**Objective of Maintaining the Quality of Construction Materials**\n\n**52.** The objective of importing construction materials and controlling the production and testing of such materials is to maintain the quality and standards of materials used in construction in the Maldives at a good level.\n\n**Import, Production, and Use of Construction Materials**\n\n**53.** Except for controlled types specified under Article 55 of this Law, any other material may be produced or imported into the Maldives and used for construction.\n\n**Testing of Construction Materials**\n\n**54.**\n(a) The Ministry shall have the authority to establish procedures related to the testing of construction materials to maintain their quality.\n(b) Construction materials shall be tested by parties licensed in accordance with the regulations for testing construction materials.\n(c) To achieve the objectives outlined in this Chapter, a laboratory capable of testing the quality of materials used in the construction sector shall be established within 12 (twelve) months from the commencement of this Law, in accordance with the regulations for testing construction materials.\n\n**Controlled Materials**\n\n**55.**\n(a) The Ministry shall have the authority to control the import and production of construction materials in the Maldives to maintain their quality and ensure their proper use.\n(b) The types of materials controlled under this Article shall be specified in the regulations for the control of import and production of construction materials made under this Law.\n(c) The controlled types of materials shall be determined by specifying the specifications or standards for such materials and their uses.\n(d) The principles for granting permits for the production and import of controlled types of materials into the Maldives shall be stipulated in the regulations for the control of import and production of construction materials made by the Ministry under this Law.\n\n**Chapter Eight: Prioritizing Maldivians in the Construction Sector**\n\n**Prioritizing Maldivians**\n\n**56.** Priority shall be given to Maldivians in carrying out construction work to the extent possible. The objectives of prioritizing Maldivians are to achieve the following:\n(a) To facilitate the increase of employment opportunities for Maldivians in the construction sector;\n(b) To ensure that work carried out in the Maldives involves the skills of Maldivians;\n(c) To provide opportunities for capable Maldivians working in the construction sector;\n(d) To create opportunities for Maldivians to provide services and offer expertise within their respective islands in the construction sector.\n\n**Achievements from Prioritizing Maldivians**\n\n**57.** The achievements sought from prioritizing Maldivians in construction work include:\n(a) Maintaining the level of foreign exchange in the Maldivian economy by providing employment opportunities for Maldivians;\n(b) Providing employment opportunities for a large segment of the working-age population throughout the Maldives;\n(c) Enhancing the skills of Maldivian workers.\n\n**Proportion of Maldivians to be Prioritized**\n\n**58.** To achieve the objectives outlined in this Chapter, the regulations to be made under Article 95 of this Law shall specify the proportions for prioritizing Maldivians.\n\n**Chapter Nine: Registration and Classification of Parties Active in the Construction Sector**\n\n**Purpose of Registration**\n\n**59.** The purpose of registering parties and activities active in the construction sector under this Law is:\n(a) To assess and record whether a party meets the quality and qualification criteria relevant to the permit; and\n(b) To ensure that parties carrying out construction work are competent for such work, recognizing that such work is technically demanding and requires safety.\n\n**Achievements from Registration**\n\n**60.** The achievements from registering parties active in the construction sector under this Law include:\n(a) Ensuring that such parties are authorized to operate and determining the status of their permits, and accessing information about their permits;\n(b) Making information about such parties publicly available;\n(c) Providing necessary information for engaging with such parties;\n(d) Facilitating the application of measures against such parties under this Law;\n(e) Making it publicly known which parties have had measures taken against them.\n\n**Areas of Registration**\n\n**61.** The Ministry shall maintain registries for the following parties or programs active in construction work under this Law:\n(a) Permit-issuing authorities for construction;\n(b) Professional parties active in the construction sector as specified in the regulations for professionals in the construction sector;\n(c) Technical parties active in the construction sector;\n(d) Construction parties;\n(e) Parties testing construction materials;\n(f) Professional associations related to construction;\n(g) Educational programs in technical and vocational fields of construction;\n(h) Parties producing and importing construction materials.\n\n**Registration Regulations**\n\n**62.**\n(a) Regulations pertaining to the registration of parties specified in Article 61 of this Law shall be made by the Ministry and published in the Government Gazette of the Maldives.\n(b) Each registration regulation made under subsection (a) of this Article shall include the following sections:\n(1) Categories of registration and the minimum eligibility criteria for each category;\n(2) Code of professional or ethical conduct;\n(3) Responsibilities of registered parties in each category of every registration;\n(4) Information on all documents required for registration and all information that must be included in the issued permit;\n(5) Duration of registration and procedures for renewal of registration;\n(6) Circumstances for cancellation and suspension of registration and measures that can be taken;\n(7) Procedures for submitting complaints regarding registered parties and for investigating such complaints;\n(8) Requirements for registration or permits under any other law.\n(c) The registration regulations for parties specified in subsections (b), (c), (d), (e), and (f) of Article 61 of this Law shall include criteria for ensuring the parties specified therein.\n\n**Public Disclosure of Registration Information**\n\n**63.** The Ministry shall publicly disclose specific information related to the registered parties, as determined by the regulations made under subsection (a) of Article 62. The procedure for publicizing such party information shall be stipulated in those regulations.\n\n**Responsibilities of Registered Parties**\n\n**64.**\n(a) Registered authorities and parties in the construction sector shall carry out all activities required under their respective permit categories in accordance with this Law and the regulations made thereunder.\n(b) If a party registered under this Law becomes aware of any activity in the construction sector occurring in violation of this Law or the regulations made thereunder, that party shall inform the permit-issuing authority for construction of the matter.\n\n**Working Without Registration or Outside Registered Category**\n\n**65.**\n(a) It is prohibited for any authority or party active in the construction sector to carry out any work outside their registered category or to falsely claim registration for work outside their category.\n(b) A party committing an act described in subsection (a) of this Article shall be subject to a fine between MVR 2,500 (two thousand five hundred) and MVR 250,000 (two hundred and fifty thousand) Rufiyaa, depending on the severity of the offense.\n(c) It is prohibited for a registered party under this Law to fail to report any changes in the information provided for registration to the Ministry.\n(d) A party committing an act described in subsection (c) of this Article shall be subject to a fine between MVR 2,000 (two thousand) and MVR 50,000 (fifty thousand) Rufiyaa, depending on the severity of the offense.\n\n**Action on Complaints Against Permitted Parties**\n\n**66.**\n(a) The Ministry shall investigate any complaint filed against a party holding a permit issued by the Ministry under this Law, in accordance with the relevant regulations, and take action against that party as specified in those regulations.\n(b) Notwithstanding subsection (a) of this Article, the Ministry shall have the authority to take action against any party who has acted in violation of this Law and the regulations made thereunder, even if that party is not registered under this Law.\n(c) Notwithstanding subsection (a) of this Article, the Ministry cannot investigate complaints related to permits issued by other parties under other laws.\n\n**Measures for Permitted Parties Violating Prescribed Standards**\n\n**67.**\n(a) If the Ministry becomes aware that a party to whom a permit has been issued under the regulations made under Article 62 of this Law has committed an act prohibited by those regulations, the Ministry, upon the recommendation of a committee appointed by the Ministry to investigate the matter, shall take measures against that party as follows:\n(1) Issuing a warning;\n(2) Ordering the party to complete a specific training if so required by a directive issued to the party;\n(3) Restricting the party\u0027s scope of work and imposing specific conditions, and recording such action in the registration;\n(4) Suspending the party\u0027s permit for a period not exceeding 12 (twelve) months, or until the party meets the required qualifications for holding the permit, and recording the suspension;\n(5) Cancelling the party\u0027s permit, removing their name from the registry, and notifying them of the period during which they may be re-issued a permit;\n(6) Imposing a fine on the party ranging from MVR 2,500 (two thousand five hundred) to MVR 250,000 (two hundred and fifty thousand) Rufiyaa, depending on the severity of the offense.\n(b) In taking measures under subsection (a) of this Article, the Ministry may impose more than one measure simultaneously, depending on the severity of the offense.\n(c) In addition to recording any measure taken by the Ministry under this Article in the registry, the Ministry may also publicly disclose information related to such measures in accordance with the procedure specified in the regulations.\n\n**Failure to Pay Fees or Fines by Permitted Parties**\n\n**68.** If any party fails to pay any amount payable under sub-point (6) of subsection (a) of Article 67 of this Law, or under subsection (b) of the same Article, within 60 (sixty) days from the date payment was due, their permit shall be suspended until the payment is made. If the payment remains outstanding after 12 (twelve) months, the party\u0027s permit shall be cancelled, and this cancellation shall be recorded in the registry.\n\n**Classification**\n\n**69.**\n(a) When classifying parties engaged in construction work, consideration shall be given to the proportion of Maldivians employed by those parties. Parties with a higher proportion of Maldivian employees shall be given more marks in the classification.\n(b) In addition to the matters described in subsection (a) of this Article, the criteria for classification shall be specified in the regulations made under this Law.\n\n**Chapter Ten: Guarantee of Payment for Services and Work Performed**\n\n**Agreement for Carrying Out Construction Work**\n\n**70.** Any construction work shall be carried out based on an agreement between the two parties for that work. The minimum components of such an agreement shall be specified in the regulations made under this Law.\n\n**Entitlement to Payment for Work, Services, and Materials**\n\n**71.**\n(a) Unless otherwise stipulated in a construction agreement, payment for construction work shall be due to the party performing the work in proportion to the amount of work completed or the value of the work performed, upon completion of specific work stages or reaching a certain value threshold.\n(b) Unless otherwise stipulated in a construction agreement, payment for construction-related services shall be due to the service provider in proportion to the extent to which the service has been provided, upon reaching a certain level of service provision.\n(c) Unless otherwise stipulated in a construction agreement, payment for materials provided for construction work shall be due to the party providing the materials in proportion to the quantity of materials supplied, upon the supply of a certain quantity of materials.\n\n**Amount of Remuneration**\n\n**72.** The remuneration or price due under Article 71 of this Law shall be calculated in one of the following two ways:\n(a) The amount of money calculated in accordance with the principles specified in the agreement; or\n(b) If the agreement does not specify the principles for calculating the payment, the value of the construction work performed, or the materials or services provided under the agreement.\n\n**Valuation of Construction Work, Materials, and Services Provided**\n\n**73.**\n(a) The construction work performed, or materials or services provided under an agreement, shall be valued as follows:\n(1) In accordance with the principles stated in the agreement; or\n(2) In circumstances not covered by the agreement, taking into account the conditions stated in subsection (b) of this Article.\n(b) For the purpose of sub-point (2) of subsection (a) of this Article, the construction work performed, or materials or services provided under an agreement, shall be valued considering the following:\n(1) The agreed price for the construction work, materials, or services;\n(2) Any other rate or price specified in the agreement;\n(3) Any agreed adjustments to the price or rate, if the parties to the agreement have mutually agreed to such adjustments;\n(4) In circumstances other than those described in sub-points (1), (2), and (3) of this paragraph, the prevailing market rate or value for such work, materials, or services at the time of performance;\n(5) The cost of rectifying any defects in the construction work, materials, or services provided;\n(6) The value of materials for which ownership transfers to the owner of the building upon payment, where such materials form part of the building.\n\n**Due Date for Payment of Remuneration**\n\n**74.**\n(a) If the payment period for work is specified in a construction agreement, the due date for payment shall be the date specified in the agreement.\n(b) If the due date for payment of work is not specified in a construction agreement, the due date shall be 30 (thirty) days from the date of submission of a valid invoice after completion of the work.\n(c) If the payment period for a specific amount of service or materials provided under an agreement is specified, the due date for payment shall be the period specified in that agreement.\n(d) If the payment period for a specific amount of service or materials provided under an agreement is not specified, the due date shall be 30 (thirty) days from the date of submission of a valid invoice after completion of the work.\n(e) Any late payment penalty shall be charged according to the principles specified in the agreement. If the agreement does not specify the method for charging penalties, the procedure specified in the regulations made under this Law shall be followed.\n\n**Prohibition of Payment Conditions Based on Receipt of Funds**\n\n**75.** Any clause in a construction agreement that states payment for work performed, services rendered, or materials supplied will only be made upon receipt of funds by any party, without specifying a time limit, shall be considered void.\n\n**Requesting Payment**\n\n**76.**\n(a) A request for payment shall be made according to the principles specified in the agreement. If no such principle is specified in the agreement, the request shall be made in accordance with the procedure specified in the regulations made under this Law.\n(b) A request for payment shall specify the amount of money being claimed and the period to which the remuneration relates. It shall also include any additional information and documents specified in the regulations made under this Law.\n\n**Responding to Payment Requests**\n\n**77.**\n(a) Upon a request for remuneration or payment under a construction agreement or an agreement for the provision of services or materials, if there are no issues with the submitted invoice, the remuneration or payment shall be made within the period specified in the agreement. If any issues are identified, they shall be stated, and a response shall be provided within the period specified in the agreement.\n(b) If the agreement does not specify a period for remuneration or payment, and if there are no issues with the submitted invoice upon a request for remuneration or payment, the remuneration or payment shall be made within 30 (thirty) days. If any issues are identified, they shall be stated, and a response shall be provided within 21 (twenty-one) days.\n(c) If excess payment has been made during the process of payment, such excess payment may be deducted from the total amount of the invoice submitted before the final remuneration or payment is made, in accordance with subsections (a) and (b) of this Article.\n\n**Chapter Eleven: Miscellaneous**\n\n**Special Sites and Items Found at Construction Sites**\n\n**78.**\n(a) If any special site or item is found at a construction site, work shall be immediately stopped, and the relevant government authority shall be notified. Action shall be taken according to the instructions of that authority. Work that has been stopped shall be resumed within 10 (ten) days through an agreement between the relevant authority and the party carrying out the work, and the work shall proceed in accordance with the agreed terms.\n(b) Failure to report special sites and items found at construction sites as described in subsection (a) of this Article shall be subject to a fine as per the administrative regulations for construction.\n\n**Prohibited Actions Within Specified Times**\n\n**79.** Failure to perform any act that is required to be performed within a specific time or within a specified period, as stipulated by this Law or regulations made thereunder, is prohibited. Similarly, failure to perform a required act after the specified time has passed is also prohibited. Violation of this Article shall be subject to measures as per Article 90 of this Law.\n\n**Review of Matters**\n\n**80.**\n(a) Any party dissatisfied with a measure taken by the permit-issuing authority for construction or the Ministry under this Law or the regulations made thereunder may submit a request for review of the matter to the Minister within 14 (fourteen) days of receiving information about the measure.\n(b) The Minister shall review the requests submitted under subsection (a) of this Article within 1 (one) month and inform the complainant and the relevant permit-issuing authority for construction of the decision.\n(c) If the matter submitted under this Article is related to a measure taken by the Ministry or the permit-issuing authority for construction in the enforcement of a court order, the Minister shall acknowledge the order and inform the complainant that no further review of the matter is possible.\n\n**Arrangements for Accessibility for Persons with Special Needs**\n\n**81.**\n(a) If the construction is for a government building or a building intended for public service, arrangements shall be made to ensure easy access for persons with special needs to such facilities.\n(b) This provision of ensuring accessibility for persons with special needs shall also apply to modifications made to such buildings constructed before the commencement of this Law.\n(c) Even if a building is not specified in subsection (a) of this Article, if public services are to be provided in that building or part thereof, arrangements shall be made to ensure easy access for persons with special needs.\n(d) If arrangements are not made as stipulated in this Article, action shall be taken against the owner of the building in accordance with the administrative regulations for construction.\n\n**Exemption of Parties Implementing the Law from Liability**\n\n**82.** No employee of the permit-issuing authority for construction or the Ministry, or any party acting on behalf of the Ministry or the permit-issuing authority for construction, shall be liable for any action taken or omitted in good faith in the performance of their duties in accordance with the law and regulations.\n\n**No Obligation to Inspect Work Progress or Verify Documentation**\n\n**83.** Except in circumstances explicitly stated in this Law or regulations made thereunder, the Ministry or the permit-issuing authority is not obligated by this Law to inspect the progress of construction work at a site or to verify the authenticity of any drawing, certificate, notice, or other document.\n\n**Party Liable for Work in Violation of the Law**\n\n**84.**\n(a) Until it is proven otherwise, the owner of the site where a violation of this Law occurs shall be considered the party responsible for the violation. If it is proven that another party is responsible for the work, that party shall be held liable for the violation.\n(b) In cases where a building owned by multiple parties is involved in a violation of this Law, and the owner of the building is liable for failure to perform a required action, the following defenses may be raised by the liable owner:\n(1) That the act was committed by another owner of the building; or\n(2) That any order or directive issued under this Law concerning the act was issued to another owner of the building.\n\n**Owner\u0027s Responsibility for Liabilities Despite Change of Ownership**\n\n**85.**\n(a) Notwithstanding any change in ownership of a building, any order or notification issued by the permit-issuing authority for construction or the Ministry to the owner of the building under this Law or the regulations made thereunder shall remain valid.\n(b) Unless otherwise agreed between the seller and the buyer of the building, the responsibility for fulfilling such an order or notification shall lie with the seller of the building.\n(c) Transactions involving changes in the ownership of a building shall be conducted after fulfilling the requirements specified in the administrative regulations for construction.\n(d) If the owner of a building has any outstanding payment to the Ministry or the permit-issuing authority for construction for actions related to the building, and unless otherwise agreed in the construction agreement, that outstanding payment shall be settled by the transferor of ownership of the building, even if the ownership of the building changes.\n\n**Detainable or Seizable Property and Items**\n\n**86.**\n(a) If no claim is made regarding the ownership of any property or item detained or seized by the permit-issuing authority for construction or the Ministry in the performance of their duties, within 20 (twenty) days from the date of detention or seizure, efforts shall be made to return such property or item to its owner in accordance with the administrative regulations for construction.\n(b) If property or an item cannot be returned as described in subsection (a) of this Article, it shall be considered property confiscated by the state, and the permit-issuing authority for construction or the Ministry shall have the power to deal with such property or item in accordance with the regulations applicable to state-confiscated property.\n(c) If any claim is made regarding the ownership of property or an item as described in subsection (a) of this Article within 20 (twenty) days, the property or item shall be returned to the claimant under specific conditions determined by the Ministry or the permit-issuing authority for construction.\n\n**Delivery of Documents**\n\n**87.** Any document, order, or notice required to be delivered to any party under this Law shall be considered duly delivered if it is delivered in accordance with the procedures specified in the administrative regulations for construction.\n\n**Obtaining Information**\n\n**88.**\n(a) If the permit-issuing authority for construction or the Ministry, in relation to a matter under its review, deems it appropriate to request information from any party, that party shall provide any information it possesses pertaining to the matter.\n(b) Failure to provide information as requested under subsection (a) of this Article, or knowingly providing false information related to the matter, is prohibited.\n\n**Verification of Authenticity of Documents**\n\n**89.**\n(a) Unless otherwise specified in this Article, all documents prepared and issued under this Law shall be presumed to be authentic unless proven otherwise.\n(b) Any document or information submitted through electronic media, presented as evidence in accordance with the administrative regulations for construction, shall be considered as evidence.\n\n**General Penalty**\n\n**90.** If no specific penalty is provided in this Law for violations thereof, the Ministry shall have the discretion to impose one or more of the following measures on the violating party, depending on the severity of the offense:\n(a) Suspension of any permit or permits issued under this Law; or\n(b) A fine not exceeding MVR 100,000 (one hundred thousand) Rufiyaa; or\n(c) Suspension of any permit as described in subsection (a) of this Article, along with a fine not exceeding MVR 100,000 (one hundred thousand) Rufiyaa; and\n(d) If any action ordered by the Ministry to rectify a situation has not been completed within the stipulated period, an additional penalty of 3% (three percent) of the fine imposable under this Article shall be levied for each day the action remains incomplete.\n\n**Applicability of the Law to the State**\n\n**91.** Unless otherwise stipulated in this Law, this Law and all regulations made thereunder shall apply equally to all state institutions.\n\n**Permits and Buildings Under Construction Prior to Commencement of the Law**\n\n**92.** Unless otherwise specified in this Law or regulations made thereunder, permits issued and work commenced prior to the commencement of this Law shall be dealt with as follows:\n(a) Valid documents, permits, or licenses issued shall be considered valid.\n(b) Notwithstanding subsection (a) of this Article, the validity period of a temporary building permit issued under any existing regulation or procedure shall be considered to be 6 (six) months from the date of commencement of this Law.\n(c) This Law shall also apply to buildings constructed in violation of regulations.\n(d) The validity period of a valid permit or license shall be considered the period determined for such permit or license under this Law and the regulations made thereunder, starting from the date of commencement of this Law.\n(e) Until regulations required to be made under this Law are formulated and implemented in accordance with Article 95 of this Law, the previously applicable regulations shall continue to be followed.\n(f) Any amendment made to a building or infrastructure constructed before the commencement of this Law or regulations made thereunder must be in compliance with this Law and the regulations made thereunder.\n\n**Procedure for Construction in Islands Without Planning Regulations and Lagoons**\n\n**93.** Construction in islands without planning regulations or in lagoons shall be carried out in accordance with the regulations concerning construction in islands without planning regulations or in lagoons.\n\n**Occurrence of Hazardous Incidents**\n\n**94.**\n(a) If information is received about a hazardous incident occurring in any building under construction or any other building, the permit-issuing authority for construction or the Ministry shall be notified. Upon receiving such information, the Ministry or the permit-issuing authority shall investigate the incident.\n(b) If the permit-issuing authority for construction receives information about a situation deemed hazardous, it shall report the matter to the Ministry. After reviewing the information in accordance with this Law and the regulations made thereunder, the Ministry may determine the incident to be hazardous.\n(c) If the situation is considered hazardous and requires work stoppage, the work shall be stopped immediately, and action shall be taken as described in this Article.\n(d) If the Ministry determines an incident to be hazardous under subsection (b) of this Article, the following actions shall be taken:\n(1) The Board shall investigate the incident and prepare a report in accordance with the administrative regulations for construction;\n(2) If the report mentioned in sub-point (1) of this paragraph recommends rectifying an issue, the Ministry shall notify the responsible party to carry out the rectification and ensure its completion.\n(e) If the party notified under subsection (d) of this Article fails to comply with the notification within the specified period, that party shall be subject to a fine between MVR 5,000 (five thousand) and MVR 500,000 (five hundred thousand) Rufiyaa, depending on the severity of the offense. If the notification is repeatedly disregarded, an additional penalty of 3% (three percent) of the imposed fine shall be added for each day the non-compliance continues.\n\n**Making of Regulations**\n\n**95.**\n(a) The Ministry shall formulate the following regulations for the implementation of this Law within 6 (six) months from the commencement date of this Law, and publish them in the Government Gazette of the Maldives:\n(1) Administrative Regulations for Construction;\n(2) Building Code;\n(3) Regulations for Professionals in the Construction Sector;\n(4) Regulations for Parties Engaged in the Practical Work of Construction;\n(5) Regulations for Safety Standards in the Practical Work of Construction;\n(6) Regulations for Materials Used in Construction and Parties Testing Such Materials;\n(7) Regulations for Educational Programs in Technical and Vocational Fields of Construction;\n(8) Regulations for Professional Associations Related to Construction;\n(9) Regulations for Appealing Decisions Made Under This Law and Regulations Made Thereunder;\n(10) Regulations for Testing Construction Materials;\n(11) Regulations for Controlling the Import and Production of Construction Materials;\n(12) Regulations for Construction in Islands Without Planning Regulations or Lagoons;\n(13) Regulations for the Registration of Permit-Issuing Authorities for Construction;\n(14) Other related regulations for construction.\n(b) Notwithstanding subsection (a) of this Article, the Administrative Regulations for Construction mentioned in sub-point (1) of subsection (a) of this Article shall be formulated by the Ministry and published in the Government Gazette of the Maldives within 1 (one) month from the commencement date of this Law.\n(c) Principles and directives issued by the Ministry in accordance with this Law and the regulations made thereunder shall be publicly disclosed. The Ministry shall ensure that such principles and directives are easily accessible.\n\n**Sections to be Included in Regulations**\n\n**96.** Regulations made under this Law shall include at least the following sections:\n(a) The Administrative Regulations for Construction shall include the following sections:\n(1) Principles for determining permit-issuing authorities for construction and use of buildings;\n(2) Responsibilities of permit-issuing authorities for construction and use of buildings;\n(3) Details of documents required when applying for construction and use permits;\n(4) Procedures for quality assessment during construction work;\n(5) Amounts and procedures for fees collected in relation to construction and use permits;\n(6) Procedures to be followed when applying for and issuing construction and use permits;\n(7) Procedures to be followed for the cancellation of construction and use permits;\n(8) Principles for imposing fines;\n(9) Other sections necessary to facilitate the administrative implementation of this Law.\n(b) The Building Code shall include the parts specified in Article 41 of this Law.\n(c) The Registration Regulations shall include the parts specified in Article 62 of this Law.\n(d) The Regulations for Professionals in the Construction Sector shall include the parts specified in Article 62 and subsection (b) of Article 69 of this Law.\n(e) The Regulations for Parties Engaged in the Practical Work of Construction shall include the parts specified in Article 62 and subsection (b) of Article 69 of this Law.\n(f) The Regulations for Safety Standards in the Practical Work of Construction shall include the following sections:\n(1) Minimum measures required for the safety and security of workers and the general public;\n(2) Measures to be taken and parties responsible for taking measures in case of violations of the regulations.\n(g) The Regulations for Materials Used in Construction and Parties Testing Such Materials shall include the parts specified in Article 62 of this Law.\n(h) The Regulations for Educational Programs in Technical and Vocational Fields of Construction shall include the following sections:\n(1) Parts specified in Article 62 of this Law;\n(2) Standards for the recognition of construction-related qualifications obtained from foreign training centers.\n(i) The Regulations for Professional Associations Related to Construction shall include the parts specified in Article 62 of this Law.\n(j) The Regulations for Appealing Decisions Made Under This Law and Regulations Made Thereunder shall include the following sections:\n(1) Matters and circumstances for which appeals can be made;\n(2) Procedures to be followed in appeals;\n(3) Period for submitting appeals;\n(4) Manner of communicating the outcome of appealed matters.\n(k) The Regulations for Testing Construction Materials shall include the following sections:\n(1) Types of materials to be tested;\n(2) Standards for testing;\n(3) Validity periods for permits issued for tested materials;\n(4) Testing locations.\n(l) The Regulations for Controlling the Import of Construction Materials shall include the following sections:\n(1) Types of materials subject to import control;\n(2) Method of assessing the quality of controlled materials;\n(3) Procedures for obtaining permits for the import of controlled materials.\n\n**Exemptions from this Law**\n\n**97.**\n(a) Construction work related to the tourism industry on uninhabited islands and atolls leased for tourism purposes, and construction of buildings not exceeding 1 (one) story for residential purposes in the outer islands, shall be exempted from this Law, as described in subsection (b) of this Article.\n(b) The conditions and standards for exemption of locations and works described in subsection (a) of this Article shall be specified in regulations to be made by the Ministry under this Law.\n(c) The regulations described in subsection (b) of this Article shall be formulated by the Ministry and published in the Government Gazette of the Maldives within 6 (six) months from the commencement date of this Law.\n\n**Commencement of the Law**\n\n**98.** This Law shall come into effect starting from the date on which 6 (six) months have passed from the date of its publication in the Government Gazette of the Maldives.\n\n**Interpretation**\n\n**99.** Unless the context otherwise requires, the following terms and phrases used in this Law shall have the meanings assigned to them below:\n(a) \"Registry\" refers to the register maintained by the Ministry containing information about parties authorized under this Law.\n(b) \"Building Code\" refers to the regulation made under sub-point (2) of subsection (a) of Article 95 of this Law, which includes standards for construction.\n(c) \"Amendment\" in relation to buildings means the repair, enlargement, reconstruction, relocation, addition to, or removal of a part of a building.\n(d) \"Construction\" refers to the erection of buildings and facilities in the built environment, or the establishment of systems. The built environment includes systems established to meet essential needs, service facilities, housing, roads, sewerage, electricity, and harbors, as well as other infrastructure development.\n(e) \"Drawings and Documentation\" refers to designs, drawings, and documents prepared for the construction of a building or for making amendments to buildings, in accordance with specific specifications.\n(f) \"Building\" refers to the following structures, including parts of buildings, unless otherwise specified in this Law:\n(1) Buildings, whether temporary or permanent, movable or immovable, used for human habitation, business, other purposes, animal husbandry, storage of machinery and goods;\n(2) Poles or communication towers, exceeding 7 (seven) meters in height from the ground level, affixed to a building or forming part of a building (excluding dish aerials not exceeding 2 (two) meters in diameter);\n(3) Temporary or permanent structures built for land retention or to prevent soil erosion;\n(4) Floating structures built or intended to be built on water, excluding boats or watercraft:\ni. A structure supported or intended to be supported on water;\nii. A structure not used or intended for navigation;\niii. A structure permanently installed or left in place.\n(5) Culverts, bridges, pedestrian crossings, tunnels, or underpasses;\n(6) Sewerage treatment plants, sewerage systems, canals, swimming pools, or any other non-proprietary tanks used for storing liquid or gas;\n(7) Structures such as wind turbines;\n(8) Facilities such as harbors, jetties, or causeways;\n(9) Structures built for coastal protection or other similar protection purposes, such as revetments;\n(10) Roads and other structures built for transportation;\n(11) Structures built or installed for carrying or retaining heavy loads.\n(g) \"Construction Permit\" refers to the permit for carrying out construction work issued by the permit-issuing authority for construction under Article 24 of this Law.\n(h) \"Permit-Issuing Authority for Construction\" refers to an authority authorized by the Ministry to issue permits for construction work, oversee such work, and provide assistance in resolving related issues.\n(i) \"Parties Active in the Construction Sector\" refers to building practitioners, construction parties, building inspectors, parties supervising construction work, and parties testing construction materials active in the construction sector.\n(j) \"Building Inspection\" refers to the examination, control, and supervision of construction work to achieve the following objectives:\n(1) To ascertain if the work is being carried out to an acceptable standard; and\n(2) To ascertain if the work is being carried out in accordance with the permit issued for that work.\n(k) \"Unsafe Building\" refers to the following types of buildings:\n(1) Buildings that are or are likely to be detrimental to health due to their location, construction method, age, deterioration, or need for repair; or\n(2) Buildings where condensation arises due to water ingress or dampness within the building, or where the system for preventing such dampness is inadequate or malfunctioning;\n(3) Buildings designed for water usage, where the water supplied to the building is unfit for consumption; or\n(4) Buildings where the sanitation facilities are inadequate for the intended use of the building.\n(l) \"Board\" refers to the Maldives Building and Construction Board established under this Law.\n(m) \"Person\" refers to both natural and legal persons.\n**Law No.: 4/2017**\n**Effective from: 23 October 2017**\n\n**Copyright © 2023 Attorney General\u0027s Office**",
