      "text": "Here\u0027s the translation of the provided text, maintaining accuracy. Please let me know if you have any questions about specific terms.\n\n## Laws of the Maldives\n\n**Law on Renting Residential Properties**\n\n**Chapter One: Preliminary**\n\n**Introduction and Name**\n\n**1.**\n(a) This is a law to specify the rights and obligations of the tenant and the landlord concerning the renting and leasing of residential properties in the Maldives, to establish the basic standards for residential rental premises, and to determine the principles for resolving disputes arising from rental transactions.\n(b) This law shall be called the \"Law on Renting Residential Properties\".\n\n**Objectives of the Law**\n\n**2.** The objectives of this law are as follows:\n(a) To specify the rights of the tenant;\n(b) To specify the rights of the landlord;\n(c) To establish the basic standards required for residential rental premises;\n(d) To determine the principles to be followed in renting residential properties;\n(e) To establish a system for the swift investigation and resolution of issues and complaints arising in connection with residential rental premises, their rent, condition, or any other related matter.\n\n**Scope of Application of the Law**\n\n**3.** This Law shall primarily apply to the following 2 (two) scopes:\n(a) To transactions between private parties concerning the renting of residential properties for living purposes; and\n(b) To transactions relating to properties provided to various parties under government housing projects.\n\n**Exemptions from the Law**\n\n**4.** Unless otherwise specified in this Law, the following premises shall be exempt from the principles and standards outlined in this Law:\n(a) Tourist hotels and guesthouses designated for providing services to tourists;\n(b) Staff accommodation designated for employees of resorts or hotels and guesthouses, or for the accommodation of the employer\u0027s staff;\n(c) Dormitories designated for students of colleges and universities;\n(d) Premises rented out on a daily basis;\n(e) Land, buildings, and other similar premises rented out for non-residential purposes, in addition to the premises specified in this Article.\n\n**Chapter Two: Enforcement of the Law**\n\n**Implementation of the Law**\n\n**5.** The Minister shall implement this Law and the regulations made thereunder.\n\n**Responsibilities and Powers of the Minister**\n\n**6.**\n(a) The primary responsibilities of the Minister under this Law include the following:\n(1) To make arrangements for all matters not specifically stipulated in this Law for its implementation;\n(2) To prepare and publish an annual report on the state of residential renting of properties in the Maldives;\n(3) To determine the basic standards required for residential rental premises;\n(4) To determine the maximum number of persons allowed to reside in each residential rental premises based on the area in square feet;\n(5) To determine the procedures for regular inspection of residential rental premises to ensure compliance with the required standards;\n(6) To determine the course of action for premises that do not comply with the standards for residential rental premises;\n(7) To establish a system for investigating and taking action on complaints related to residential rental premises;\n(8) To study residential rental premises in the Maldives and changes in their rent;\n(9) To conduct programs in collaboration with state institutions to raise public awareness regarding the protection of the rights of landlords and tenants of residential rental premises;\n(10) To oversee and provide guidance on the responsibilities assigned to Councils for the implementation of this Law;\n(11) To determine the principles for collecting fees for services provided under this Law.\n(b) The Minister shall have all powers necessary for the administration and enforcement of this Law and for the fulfillment of the responsibilities outlined in subsection (a) of this Article.\n\n**Decentralized Service Delivery**\n\n**7.** The Ministry shall make arrangements for the decentralized implementation of this Law throughout all regions of the Maldives, in collaboration with Councils, and in accordance with the regulations made under this Law.\n\n**Chapter Three: Registration of Rental Premises and Obtaining Permits**\n\n**Obtaining a Rental Permit**\n\n**8.**\n(a) Any premises falling within the scope of this Law shall be rented for residential purposes only after applying for a rental permit to the City Council of the respective city or the Island Council of the respective island, in accordance with the principles set forth in this Law, and after registering the premises as a rental premise.\n(b) It is prohibited to rent out any premises for residential purposes without a rental permit.\n\n**Conditions to be Ensured for Issuance of Rental Permits**\n\n**9.** Upon application for a rental permit under subsection (a) of Article 8 of this Law, Councils shall ensure the following when issuing the permit:\n(a) That the application for the rental permit has been submitted by the owner of the premises for which the permit is sought, or by another party authorized by the owner;\n(b) That the premises for which a rental permit is sought meet all the requirements specified in this Law and the regulations made thereunder for residential rental premises.\n\n**Registry of Rental Premises**\n\n**10.**\n(a) A registry of all premises permitted for residential renting in the Maldives shall be maintained as follows, in accordance with this Law and the regulations made thereunder:\n(1) The City Council of each city, and the Island Council of each island, shall maintain a registry of all premises for which rental permits have been issued in that city or island, in accordance with this Law and the regulations made thereunder, after issuing the permits;\n(2) The Ministry shall maintain a registry of all premises for which residential rental permits have been issued throughout the Maldives, in accordance with this Law and the regulations made thereunder.\n(b) Within 3 (three) days of issuing a residential rental permit, the permit-issuing Council shall inform the Ministry of the issuance of such permit.\n(c) The Ministry shall establish a system within 6 (six) months from the commencement date of this Law, which allows easy access to information about registered residential rental premises via the internet for anyone who needs to view such information.\n(d) If the entire building is not registered as a rental premises, and if only specific parts or floors of the building are rented out, such premises shall be registered individually as rental premises in accordance with Article 8 of this Law.\n\n**Basic Standards for Rental Premises**\n\n**11.**\n(a) All rental premises under this Law shall meet the following basic standards:\n(1) Availability of water, sewerage, and electricity services installed in accordance with standards set by the relevant state authorities;\n(2) If the rental premises is a building or part of a building, there shall be an arrangement for separate access to and from the premises without hindering the use of other parts of the building and without causing inconvenience;\n(3) If the rental premises is a building, it shall be a building or part of a building that meets the standards set forth in Law No. 4/2017 (Law on Construction);\n(4) The premises shall be designed for sleeping and dining.\n(b) The basic standards required for all rental premises under this Law shall be detailed in the regulations made under this Law.\n\n**Chapter Four: Rental Agreements and Rent**\n\n**Landlord**\n\n**12.**\n(a) For the purposes of this Law, the landlord shall be the owner of the building or any party authorized by the owner to rent out the building.\n(b) If a rental premises is rented out by more than one party jointly, all such parties shall be considered as the landlord for the purposes of this Law.\n\n**Tenant**\n\n**13.**\n(a) For the purposes of this Law, the tenant shall be the party who leases a premises for residential purposes under a rental agreement.\n(b) If a premises is leased by more than one party jointly, all such parties shall be considered as the tenant for the purposes of this Law.\n\n**Signing of Rental Agreements**\n\n**14.**\n(a) After the commencement of this Law, any premises in any region of the Maldives shall be rented for residential purposes for a period exceeding 6 (six) months only after a written agreement is concluded between the landlord and the tenant, signed by both parties in the presence of 2 (two) witnesses, in accordance with the provisions of this Law.\n(b) The rental agreement must fulfill all conditions that are made mandatory by this Law and the regulations made thereunder.\n(c) Within 10 (ten) days of signing the rental agreement and renting out a premises for residential purposes, the landlord shall inform the City Council of the respective city or the Island Council of the respective island about the rental agreement.\n(d) The procedures for informing the Councils about the rental of premises for residential purposes after signing a rental agreement, as described in subsection (c) of this Article, shall be formulated and published by the Councils.\n(e) The Council shall inform the Ministry about the rental of premises for residential purposes within a minimum of 15 (fifteen) days from the date of being notified as per subsection (c) of this Article.\n(f) Any expenses incurred in concluding a rental agreement shall be borne by the landlord.\n(g) If the landlord is aware of any issue lodged with any authority concerning the premises before the tenant signs the rental agreement, the landlord shall provide the tenant with complete information regarding that matter in writing.\n\n**Contents of Rental Agreements**\n\n**15.**\n(a) The rental agreement, as described in Article 14 of this Law, shall include all of the following:\n(1) The landlord\u0027s full name, permanent address, residential address, national identification card number, and contact phone number (if the landlord is a business, its business registration number);\n(2) Information about the owner of the premises if the landlord is not the owner;\n(3) The land registration number if the rental premises is land;\n(4) Information about the registered party of the premises if the rental premises is a building;\n(5) The rental permit number and the date of issuance of the permit for renting out the premises;\n(6) The building use permit number for the rental premises;\n(7) The tenant\u0027s full name, permanent address, residential address, national identification card number or passport number, and contact phone number (if the tenant is a business, its business registration number);\n(8) The tenant\u0027s visa number if the tenant is a foreigner;\n(9) The address or email address for sending documents to the tenant and the landlord;\n(10) The area of the rental premises (in square feet);\n(11) The rent for the rental premises;\n(12) The method of rent payment;\n(13) If rent is to be deposited into a bank account designated by the landlord, the name and number of the account, and information about the bank where the account is held;\n(14) The commencement date and expiry date of the rental agreement, and the duration of the agreement;\n(15) Periods for issuing notices as per the agreement;\n(16) The date of signing the rental agreement;\n(17) The agreed method for collecting a security deposit under the rental agreement, in accordance with this Law;\n(18) Meter numbers for the basic services of the rental premises and information related to such services;\n(19) The rights and responsibilities of the tenant under the rental agreement;\n(20) The rights and responsibilities of the landlord under the rental agreement;\n(21) Whether the tenant has the right to sublet the rental premises under the rental agreement;\n(22) Methods for amending the rental agreement and procedures for renewing the agreement;\n(23) Procedures to be followed in case of disputes regarding the rental agreement;\n(24) Circumstances under which the rental agreement may be terminated;\n(25) Notice period required for terminating the rental agreement and procedures related to such notice;\n(26) Procedures for vacating and handing over the rental premises upon termination or expiry of the rental agreement;\n(27) The condition in which the premises should be left upon vacating and handover;\n(28) If the building is mortgaged, information about this, and details of any ongoing legal proceedings related to the building;\n(29) If a party to the rental agreement dies during the term of the agreement, the procedure to be followed regarding the agreement.\n(b) In addition to the information specified in subsection (a) of this Article, the following documents shall be included as part of the rental agreement:\n(1) A copy of the rental permit for the rental premises and documentation of its registration for renting;\n(2) A copy of the national identification card or passport of the landlord and tenant (if the party is a business, documentation of business registration);\n(3) If the tenant is a foreigner, a copy of their valid visa, and if employed, proof of employment;\n(4) If the landlord is not the owner of the building, a document authorizing the landlord to rent out the building;\n(5) An inventory list of the contents of the rental premises.\n\n**Prohibited Clauses in Rental Agreements**\n\n**16.** The following clauses shall not be included in a rental agreement:\n(a) A clause prohibiting the accommodation of persons based on nationality, region, ethnicity, gender, ideology, or disability;\n(b) A clause prohibiting the presence of persons of a specific age group in the rental premises;\n(c) A clause prohibiting tenants from entering or exiting the building at specific times;\n(d) A clause requiring the tenant to pay any amount in addition to the rent and security deposit, except for costs related to essential repairs or utility bills that are to be paid by the tenant, or rents and security deposits;\n(e) A clause prohibiting the refund of the security deposit;\n(f) A clause requiring the tenant to commit any act that violates social norms;\n(g) A clause reducing the notice period for terminating the rental agreement without the tenant\u0027s consent, to less than that stipulated in this Law.\n\n**Determination of Occupancy Limit Per Premises**\n\n**17.** The landlord has the right to determine the number of persons who can reside in a rental premises, not exceeding the maximum occupancy limit determined for that premises based on its area in square feet and its classification, in accordance with sub-point (4) of subsection (a) of Article 6 of this Law.\n\n**Collection of Security Deposit**\n\n**18.**\n(a) The landlord has the right to determine the security deposit amount, which shall not exceed the equivalent of 2 (two) months\u0027 rent.\n(b) The security deposit amount specified in subsection (a) of this Article shall be paid by the tenant either by depositing it into an account designated by the landlord or by handing it over to the landlord.\n(c) The landlord shall provide the tenant with a written receipt for the security deposit amount received.\n(d) If the rental agreement is terminated for any reason, the security deposit amount handed over shall be returned to the tenant within a maximum of 15 (fifteen) days, taking into account the provisions of subsection (e) of this Article.\n(e) When returning the security deposit amount in accordance with subsection (d) of this Article, the landlord shall consider the following:\n(1) Deducting unpaid utility bills for the rental premises from the security deposit amount when the tenant vacates the premises;\n(2) Deducting the cost of repairing any damage caused to items fixed in the rental premises due to the tenant\u0027s negligence from the security deposit;\n(3) Deducting the cost of repairing any damage to the movable property handed over to the tenant for use, other than normal wear and tear, from the security deposit;\n(4) Deducting any unpaid rent from the security deposit amount when the tenant vacates the premises.\n(f) If no deductions are required from the security deposit amount as per subsection (e) of this Article, the entire amount of the security deposit shall be returned to the tenant in one lump sum within the period specified in subsection (d) of this Article.\n\n**Determination of Rent**\n\n**19.**\n(a) The rent for each rental premises and the method of payment shall be specified in the rental agreement when renting out the premises for residential purposes.\n(b) The rent determined shall be the amount payable by the tenant to the landlord on a monthly basis, or in a lump sum for the entire duration of the agreement, or in any other manner agreed upon by both parties, in exchange for the tenant\u0027s right to use the premises for residential purposes during the period of the agreement.\n(c) If the consideration for the rental premises is other than monetary, this shall be clearly stated in the rental agreement.\n\n**Prohibition of Rent Increases**\n\n**20.**\n(a) The rent specified in the rental agreement shall not be altered during the term of the agreement.\n(b) This Article does not preclude the determination of different rent amounts for different periods within the total term of the agreement, as mutually agreed upon by both parties at the time of concluding the rental agreement.\n\n**Maintenance of Rent Records**\n\n**21.**\n(a) The tenant and the landlord shall jointly maintain written records of rent payments made by the tenant to the landlord throughout the duration of the agreement, until the expiry of the agreement period.\n(b) If rent is paid in cash, the landlord shall provide the tenant with a receipt for the payment.\n(c) If rent is paid into a bank account designated by the landlord, the tenant shall retain the proof of deposit. The tenant shall also provide the landlord with a copy of the proof of deposit.\n\n**Advance Rent Collection**\n\n**22.**\n(a) Except in cases where the total rent for the entire duration of the rental agreement is collected in advance, or where rent is collected in advance for a period agreed upon by both parties, it is prohibited for the landlord to collect rent or any other payment in advance from the tenant for a rented premises.\n(b) No clause shall be included in the rental agreement to permit the collection of rent in advance in contravention of subsection (a) of this Article. Furthermore, the landlord shall not solicit any advance payment outside the terms of the agreement.\n\n**Amendment to Rental Agreements**\n\n**23.** A rental agreement can be amended only by the mutual consent of both the landlord and the tenant, and through a written amendment.\n\n**Transfer of Rights Under Rental Agreements**\n\n**24.**\n(a) The tenant\u0027s rights under a rental agreement may be transferred to a third party with the written consent of the landlord.\n(b) Upon the transfer of the tenant\u0027s rights under a rental agreement to a third party, all rights of the tenant under the agreement shall transfer to the third party, in addition to all of the tenant\u0027s responsibilities and obligations also transferring to the third party.\n(c) If the tenant applies to the landlord for permission to transfer their rights under the rental agreement to a third party, the landlord shall not unreasonably withhold such permission.\n(d) If the tenant applies to the landlord for permission to transfer their rights under the rental agreement to a third party, the landlord shall not charge any additional fee from the tenant for granting such permission.\n\n**Subletting by Tenant**\n\n**25.**\n(a) The tenant may sublet the rental premises to another party only with the written consent of both the tenant and the landlord, as per the rental agreement.\n(b) In cases of subletting by the tenant as described in subsection (a) of this Article, all principles for renting out premises for residential purposes under this Law shall be followed.\n\n**Termination of Rental Agreements**\n\n**26.** A rental agreement shall be terminated under the following circumstances:\n(a) Mutual written agreement between the landlord and the tenant to terminate the rental agreement;\n(b) Expiry of the rental agreement period without renewal by agreement of both parties;\n(c) Issuance of notice by one party to the other party to terminate the rental agreement, in accordance with the provisions of the rental agreement, and the expiry of the notice period;\n(d) A court ruling declaring the rental agreement to be unenforceable;\n(e) In the case of a mortgaged property, a court order for the enforcement of the mortgage.\n\n**Termination of Rental Agreements by the Landlord**\n\n**27.** The landlord may terminate the rental agreement in accordance with the procedures specified in this Article.\n(a) In cases where the tenant breaches the rental agreement and the landlord wishes to terminate the agreement, the landlord shall issue a written notice to the tenant stating the breach, the landlord\u0027s intention to terminate the agreement, and detailing the tenant\u0027s contraventions as identified by the landlord. The notice shall also specify the reasons for termination, the consequences of non-compliance, the period within which the tenant must rectify the breaches, the date on which the agreement will be terminated if breaches are not rectified, and the requirement for the tenant to vacate the premises by the termination date.\n(b) Notwithstanding subsection (a) of this Article, if the landlord wishes to terminate the rental agreement for their own use before the expiry of the agreement period, and if the premises are not rented to more than one party, termination may occur under the following circumstances:\n(1) If the building requires major repairs that cannot be carried out with the tenants residing therein, necessitating the vacation of the premises;\n(2) If the landlord wishes to reside in the rental premises;\n(3) If the landlord\u0027s parents, spouse, children, or grandchildren require accommodation in the rental premises;\n(4) If the landlord needs to sell the rental premises.\n(c) If the landlord wishes to vacate the premises for their own use, a notice of at least 3 (three) months shall be given to the tenant.\n(d) If a complaint is filed with the Council within 1 (one) year of termination based on the landlord\u0027s personal use claim, alleging that the landlord has rented out the premises to another party or used it for another purpose, and if the Council investigates and confirms the complaint, the landlord shall be liable for a fine not exceeding MVR 50,000 (fifty thousand) Rufiyaa.\n(e) Notwithstanding subsections (a) and (b) of this Article, if the rental premises are jointly owned by more than one party, or if the landlord is more than one party, the rental agreement cannot be terminated without the tenant\u0027s consent, unless it is in accordance with this Law.\n(f) If the landlord wishes to terminate the rental agreement due to the tenant\u0027s breach of the agreement, the landlord shall provide the tenant with a notice of at least 2 (two) months.\n(g) Upon termination of the rental agreement in accordance with this Article, the landlord shall inform the City Council of the respective city or the Island Council of the respective island about the termination.\n\n**Prohibition of Landlord Terminating Agreement Without Cause**\n\n**28.** The landlord cannot terminate the rental agreement without informing the tenant of the reason for termination. Furthermore, the reason stated for termination must be a valid reason for termination as specified in this Law and the rental agreement.\n\n**Termination of Rental Agreements by the Tenant**\n\n**29.**\n(a) Unless otherwise stipulated in the rental agreement, the tenant has the right to terminate the agreement by giving a notice of at least 1 (one) month to the landlord if the tenant wishes to terminate the agreement before the expiry of the rental period due to the landlord\u0027s breach of the agreement or due to the tenant\u0027s desire to vacate the premises.\n(b) In cases where the tenant wishes to terminate the rental agreement, the tenant has the right to terminate the agreement after paying the rent up to the expiry of the notice period and vacating the premises.\n\n**Permitted Duration for Residential Rentals**\n\n**30.**\n(a) Notwithstanding any other law, a building or part of a building may be rented out for residential purposes for a duration agreed upon by both parties, based on a mutual agreement between the landlord and the tenant.\n(b) Upon the expiry of the term of an agreement concluded under subsection (a) of this Article, the premises may be re-rented under a new agreement.\n\n**Extension of Rental Agreement Period**\n\n**31.** If it is desired to extend the period of a rental agreement for a premises, the agreement period may be extended by mutual agreement of both parties before the expiry of the current agreement period.\n\n**Chapter Five: Rights and Obligations Arising from Rental Agreements**\n\n**Consequences of Rental Agreements**\n\n**32.** Unless otherwise specified in this Law or the regulations made thereunder, it is legally established that the premises rented under a rental agreement, as per Article 41 of this Law, is for the use of the tenant without the involvement of any other party.\n\n**Obligations of the Landlord**\n\n**33.** The landlord shall fulfill the following:\n(a) To ensure and inform the tenant, before renting out the premises, that the premises is legally permitted for renting;\n(b) If the premises is mortgaged, or if there are any ongoing legal proceedings related to the premises with any authority or court, to provide the tenant with written information about such matters, and if any attempt is being made to initiate such proceedings, to provide information about that as well, before the signing of the rental agreement;\n(c) During the term of the rental agreement, not to obstruct the tenant\u0027s use of the rented premises in any way;\n(d) Not to obstruct the tenant from obtaining any services necessary for the use of the rented premises;\n(e) To make arrangements for the tenant to have unimpeded access to and from the rented premises;\n(f) To specify in the rental agreement the procedure for carrying out necessary repairs to the building during the rental period;\n(g) To facilitate the tenant in obtaining services such as internet and cable TV, including obtaining the landlord\u0027s permission or signature when required;\n(h) If the tenant breaches the rental agreement during the term of the agreement, to act in accordance with the principles specified in the agreement and the regulations made under this Law;\n(i) To provide the tenant with the opportunity to negotiate the rent for the purpose of reaching a rental agreement.\n\n**Obligations of the Tenant**\n\n**34.** The tenant shall fulfill the following:\n(a) To pay the rent to the landlord regularly as specified in the rental agreement;\n(b) Not to use the rented premises for any purpose other than residential use;\n(c) To keep the rented premises clean and maintained;\n(d) To dispose of or eliminate waste generated in the rented premises according to the arrangements made for waste management within the premises;\n(e) Not to make any alterations to the rented premises without the landlord\u0027s permission;\n(f) If any damage occurs to the rented premises, to immediately inform the landlord of the damage and to carry out repairs as specified in the rental agreement;\n(g) Not to use the rented premises for any illegal purpose;\n(h) Not to exceed the number of occupants determined for the rented premises based on the determined ratio per square foot, as stipulated by this Law.\n\n**Prohibition of Subletting to Multiple Parties**\n\n**35.** While the rental agreement is in effect, the landlord shall not rent out the premises to any party other than the original tenant.\n\n**Handover of Rental Premises**\n\n**36.** The rental premises shall be handed over to the tenant after completing all the conditions specified in the rental agreement for the handover of the premises.\n\n**Right to Peaceful Enjoyment of Rental Premises**\n\n**37.**\n(a) The tenant has the right to use the rental premises peacefully, like their own residence, throughout the lease term.\n(b) It is prohibited for the landlord or their representative to cause any disturbance or obstruction to the tenant\u0027s right of peaceful enjoyment as described in subsection (a) of this Article.\n(c) Notwithstanding subsection (b) of this Article, the tenant shall facilitate the landlord\u0027s entry into the rental premises under the following circumstances:\n(1) To inspect the condition of the premises, with prior notice of at least 24 (twenty-four) hours to the tenant;\n(2) In the event of a hazardous incident;\n(3) For the purpose of carrying out repairs, after notifying the tenant before commencing the work.\n(d) If the landlord intends to carry out structural repairs or any other work that may cause disturbance in the building where the rental premises is located, the tenant shall be notified 24 (twenty-four) hours prior to the commencement of such work.\n\n**Payment of Dues and Utility Bills**\n\n**38.**\n(a) When handing over the premises to the tenant, the landlord shall ensure that all outstanding payments and utility bills related to the premises are settled.\n(b) Notwithstanding subsection (a) of this Article, if the landlord has any long-term liabilities related to the premises or building, the landlord shall be responsible for settling such payments within the lease term.\n(c) The tenant shall be responsible for paying bills for all services utilized by the tenant in the rented premises during the term of the rental agreement.\n\n**Vacation and Handover of Premises**\n\n**39.** Upon the termination or expiry of the rental agreement, the tenant shall hand over the rental premises to the landlord in accordance with the terms of the rental agreement.\n\n**Chapter Six: Establishment of a Complaint System**\n\n**Submission of Complaints**\n\n**40.** Both the tenant and the landlord have the right to submit complaints to the Island Council of the respective island or the City Council of the respective city regarding any issue related to a rental agreement under this Law, the rental premises, or any other rental transaction.\n\n**Initial Submission of Complaints**\n\n**41.**\n(a) Complaints submitted under Article 40 of this Law shall be submitted to the City Council if the premises is located in a city, and to the Island Council if the premises is located on an island.\n(b) Upon submission of a complaint as described in subsection (a) of this Article, the Council shall make a decision on the complaint within 7 (seven) days of receiving it and inform the complainant of the decision.\n(c) The procedures to be followed by the Councils in handling complaints under this Article shall be specified in the regulations made under this Law.\n\n**Submission of Council Decisions to Court**\n\n**42.**\n(a) If either party to a complaint is dissatisfied with a decision made by the Council as being unlawful or unjust, that party has the right to submit the decision to the court within 30 (thirty) days of receiving the decision.\n(b) If no party submits the Council\u0027s decision to the court within 30 (thirty) days of the decision being made, it shall be considered that the right to challenge the decision has been waived.\n\n**Enforcement of Council Decisions**\n\n**43.**\n(a) If no party submits the Council\u0027s decision to the court within 30 (thirty) days of the decision being made, the Council shall ensure that the decision is enforced. If the decision has not been enforced, the Council may submit the decision to the court for enforcement.\n(b) In matters submitted to the court under subsection (a) of this Article, the court shall not review the merits of the case, but rather the Council\u0027s compliance with the stipulated procedures.\n\n**Court Review of Matters**\n\n**44.**\n(a) Matters submitted to the court in relation to a Council decision shall be filed with the civil court having jurisdiction over the city or island where the rental premises is located.\n(b) Matters described in subsection (a) of this Article shall be handled as urgent matters.\n(c) In every matter submitted to the court concerning a Council decision, the court shall review the Council\u0027s proceedings.\n\n**Exemption of Matters Subject to Arbitration**\n\n**45.** Notwithstanding anything to the contrary in this Law, if a rental agreement specifies that any dispute arising from the agreement shall be resolved through arbitration, such a dispute shall only be adjudicated by the court in accordance with Law No. 10/2013 (Arbitration Law).\n\n**Chapter Seven: Special Provisions**\n\n**Provisions Relating to Properties Provided Under Housing Projects**\n\n**46.**\n(a) Special regulations shall be made under this Law for the renting of houses, flats, and plots provided under government social housing projects.\n(b) Although special regulations for properties provided under government social housing projects are stipulated in the regulations mentioned in subsection (a) of this Article, the provisions of this Law regarding the contents of rental agreements, notification to Councils, and submission of complaints shall also apply to such properties.\n(c) The regulations described in subsection (a) of this Article shall include the following:\n(1) Rental period;\n(2) Prohibition of renting out the entire premises;\n(3) Non-application of these regulations if ownership of the premises has been transferred and registered in the name of the party to whom the property was granted.\n\n**Regulations Relating to Boarding Houses**\n\n**47.**\n(a) Boarding houses shall be operated only after registration in accordance with the regulations made under this Law.\n(b) A person may reside in a boarding house only under an agreement concluded between the boarding house operator and the resident.\n(c) Notwithstanding subsection (b) of this Article, a child may reside in a boarding house that accommodates children only under an agreement concluded between the boarding house operator and the child\u0027s guardian, in accordance with the provisions for such agreements.\n\n**Renting Out Premises for Construction Purposes**\n\n**48.** This Law does not prevent the renting out of land for construction purposes for a long-term period, followed by the renting out of the constructed building for residential use, based on an agreement between the landlord and the tenant.\n\n**Chapter Eight: General Provisions**\n\n**Making and Enforcement of Regulations**\n\n**49.**\n(a) The following regulations shall be made by the Ministry and published in the Government Gazette of the Maldives:\n(1) General Regulations on Renting Residential Properties;\n(2) Regulations on Procedures for Councils to Handle Complaints;\n(3) Regulations detailing the basic standards required for residential rental premises;\n(4) Regulations on Procedures for Inspecting Residential Rental Premises;\n(5) Special Regulations on Renting Houses, Flats, and Plots Provided Under Government Housing Projects;\n(6) Special Regulations on Renting Out Premises as Boarding Houses.\n(b) Unless otherwise specified in this Law, all regulations required to be made under this Law shall be made by the Ministry.\n(c) Unless otherwise specified in this Law, all regulations required to be made under this Law shall be made and published in the Government Gazette of the Maldives within 90 (ninety) days from the commencement date of this Law.\n\n**Commencement of the Law**\n\n**50.** This Law shall come into effect from the date it is passed, ratified, and published in the Government Gazette of the Maldives.\n\n**Priority of this Law**\n\n**51.** Notwithstanding any other law or regulation, priority shall be given to this Law in the renting of all residential properties in the Maldives after the commencement of this Law.\n\n**Imposition of Fines and Penalties**\n\n**52.**\n(a) Unless otherwise specified in this Law, Councils shall have the discretion to impose measures on parties violating this Law and the regulations made thereunder, in escalating sequence, based on the extent of the violation and in accordance with the principles detailed in the regulations made under this Law:\n(1) First violation - a fine of MVR 1,000 (one thousand) Rufiyaa;\n(2) For each subsequent violation - a fine of MVR 3,000 (three thousand) Rufiyaa.\n(b) Any fine imposed under this Law for a violation shall be paid within 7 (seven) days from the date of imposition, in accordance with the procedures specified in the regulations made under this Law.\n\n**Existing Rental Agreements**\n\n**53.**\n(a) Existing agreements for rented residential premises at the time of commencement of this Law shall continue to be enforced.\n(b) Within 6 (six) months from the commencement date of this Law, information on existing agreements for rented residential premises shall be reported to the Council in accordance with Article 14 of this Law and the regulations made thereunder.\n(c) In resolving disputes arising from existing agreements for rented residential premises, in the absence of contrary provisions in those agreements, the procedures specified in this Law and the regulations made thereunder shall be followed.\n(d) If an existing rental agreement for residential premises requires renewal after the commencement of this Law, the renewed rental agreement shall comply with all the provisions of this Law.\n(e) Special regulations for existing rental premises shall be stipulated in the regulations made under this Law.\n\n**Repeal of Laws and Regulations**\n\n**54.** Upon the commencement of this Law, the following laws and regulations shall be repealed:\n(a) Article 28 of Law No. 1/2002 (Maldives Land Law).\n(b) All articles related to residential rentals in the \"Regulations on Land and Buildings Constructed on Land\".\n\n**Interpretation**\n\n**55.** Unless the context otherwise requires, the following terms and phrases used in this Law shall have the meanings assigned to them below:\n(a) \"Renting\" refers to the right granted to a tenant to use a premises for residential purposes for a specified period, in exchange for rent, without transfer of ownership.\n(b) \"Rental Agreement\" refers to the agreement concluded between the landlord and the tenant, including all schedules contained therein, any amendments or additions made to any other agreement for renting out, and all related documentation.\n(c) \"Minister\" refers to the Minister of the government ministry responsible for housing, construction, and urban development.\n(d) \"Ministry\" refers to the government ministry responsible for housing, construction, and urban development.\n(e) \"Landlord\" refers to the party as defined in Article 12 of this Law.\n(f) \"Tenant\" refers to the party as defined in Article 13 of this Law.\n(g) \"Rental Premises\" refers to a premises made available for use by the tenant for a specified period under a rental agreement.\n(h) \"Renting for Residential Purposes\" refers to the provision of a building, part of a building, or land to another party for residential use for a specified period, in exchange for rent, without transfer of ownership.\n(i) \"Councils\" refers to Island Councils, Atoll Councils, and City Councils as defined in Law No. 7/2010 (Decentralization Act of the Maldives).\n(j) \"Boarding House\" refers to a house that provides accommodation, food, and other basic living services for a specified fee for a specified period, and allows the use of common areas of the house.\n(k) \"Guardian\" refers to parents, legal guardians, custodians, and any person legally responsible for the care of a child at any given time. Legal guardians, custodians, and legally responsible persons shall be interpreted in accordance with Law No. 4/2000 (Family Law) and the regulations made thereunder.\n**Law No.: 21/2021**\n**Effective from: 18 November 2021**\n\n**Copyright © 2023 Attorney General\u0027s Office**",
