      "text": "A **condominium**, often shortened to **condo**, is a type of property ownership where an individual owns a specific unit within a larger building or complex.\n\nHere\u0027s a breakdown of what that means:\n\n*   **Individual Unit Ownership:** You own the \"airspace\" within the boundaries of your specific unit. This includes the interior walls, floors, and ceilings.\n*   **Shared Ownership of Common Areas:** You jointly own, along with all other unit owners, the common areas and amenities of the building or complex. This can include things like hallways, elevators, lobbies, roofs, exteriors, recreational facilities (pools, gyms), and the land the building sits on.\n*   **Management and Fees:** Condo owners typically pay monthly fees (often called condo fees or association fees) to a governing association or management corporation. This association is responsible for maintaining the common areas, amenities, and shared resources.\n*   **Restrictive Covenants:** Condo titles often come with restrictive covenants that dictate how owners can use and maintain their units.\n\nIn essence, a condominium offers a way to own your private living space while sharing the responsibility and costs of maintaining the shared parts of the property. It\u0027s a key distinction from renting an apartment, where you only have the right to occupy the unit.",
